From: Stephen Wheet <stephen@wheetazlab.io>
Date: Sat, 7 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] net: macb: fix TX stall on RP1 over PCIe with fence and retry

The RP1 southbridge on Raspberry Pi CM5 / Pi 5 exposes the Cadence GEM
(macb) ethernet controller behind a PCIe link.  Two distinct failure modes
cause TX stalls under sustained load:

1. Posted TSTART writes silently dropped over PCIe.  PCIe uses posted
   writes for MMIO: the CPU fires the write and moves on.  Under load the
   NCR |= TSTART write can be silently lost, leaving the TX ring stalled.

2. Hardware ignores TSTART because the transmitter is already active.
   When the TGO bit is set in TSR, the GEM hardware may discard a new
   TSTART assertion, so the queued descriptors are never transmitted.

Fix mode 1 by following every TSTART write with readl() (non-relaxed).
On arm64, readl() includes a DSB instruction which stalls the CPU until
the resulting PCIe non-posted read completes, creating a protocol-level
ordering fence that guarantees TSTART has reached RP1.

Fix mode 2 by adopting the Raspberry Pi downstream approach (rpi-6.12.y,
commit 359f37f / e45c98d by Jonathan Bell): before writing TSTART in
macb_start_xmit(), check if TGO is already set.  If so, mark
queue->tx_pending = 1.  In the interrupt handler, check tx_pending
alongside TXUBR and set txubr_pending so the NAPI TX poll calls
macb_tx_restart() to retry.  This adds a tx_pending field to struct
macb_queue in macb.h.

Observed symptom on DeskPi Super6C (CM5, Talos Linux 1.12.x / kernel
6.18.x): controller nodes become unreachable under heavy NVMe I/O
(minio on PCIe NVMe) after minutes to hours.  etcd reports "failed to
reach the peer URL" with i/o timeout.  A readl() fence alone proved
insufficient under sustained PCIe load; the combined approach addresses
both failure modes.

Link: https://github.com/siderolabs/sbc-raspberrypi/issues/82
Link: https://github.com/raspberrypi/linux/commit/e45c98decbb16e58a79c7ec6fbe4374320e814f1
Signed-off-by: Stephen Wheet <stephen@wheetazlab.io>
---
 drivers/net/ethernet/cadence/macb.h      |  1 +
 drivers/net/ethernet/cadence/macb_main.c | 15 ++++++++++++++-
 2 files changed, 15 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/drivers/net/ethernet/cadence/macb.h b/drivers/net/ethernet/cadence/macb.h
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/cadence/macb.h
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/cadence/macb.h
@@ -1260,6 +1260,7 @@ struct macb_queue {
 	struct work_struct	tx_error_task;
 	bool			txubr_pending;
+	unsigned int		tx_pending;
 	struct napi_struct	napi_tx;
 
 	dma_addr_t		rx_ring_dma;
diff --git a/drivers/net/ethernet/cadence/macb_main.c b/drivers/net/ethernet/cadence/macb_main.c
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/cadence/macb_main.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/cadence/macb_main.c
@@ -1717,6 +1717,10 @@ static void macb_tx_restart(struct macb_queue *queue)
 
 	spin_lock(&bp->lock);
 	macb_writel(bp, NCR, macb_readl(bp, NCR) | MACB_BIT(TSTART));
+	/* RP1 is behind PCIe; posted TSTART writes can be silently dropped.
+	 * readl() (non-relaxed) includes DSB on arm64 — the CPU stalls until
+	 * the PCIe non-posted read completes, fencing TSTART to RP1. */
+	(void)readl(bp->regs + MACB_NCR);
 	spin_unlock(&bp->lock);
 
 out_tx_ptr_unlock:
@@ -1931,9 +1935,10 @@ static irqreturn_t macb_interrupt(int irq, void *dev_id)
 				queue_writel(queue, ISR, MACB_BIT(TCOMP) |
 							 MACB_BIT(TXUBR));
 
-			if (status & MACB_BIT(TXUBR)) {
+			if (status & MACB_BIT(TXUBR) || queue->tx_pending) {
 				queue->txubr_pending = true;
+				queue->tx_pending = 0;
 				wmb(); // ensure softirq can see update
 			}
 
@@ -2390,7 +2395,14 @@ static netdev_tx_t macb_start_xmit(struct sk_buff *skb, struct net_device *dev)
 			     skb->len);
 
 	spin_lock(&bp->lock);
-	macb_writel(bp, NCR, macb_readl(bp, NCR) | MACB_BIT(TSTART));
+	/* If TX DMA is already active (TGO set), TSTART may be ignored by
+	 * hardware.  Flag this so the IRQ handler retriggers via NAPI poll. */
+	if (macb_readl(bp, TSR) & MACB_BIT(TGO))
+		queue->tx_pending = 1;
+	macb_writel(bp, NCR, macb_readl(bp, NCR) | MACB_BIT(TSTART));
+	/* RP1 is behind PCIe; posted TSTART writes can be silently dropped.
+	 * readl() (non-relaxed) includes DSB on arm64 — the CPU stalls until
+	 * the PCIe non-posted read completes, fencing TSTART to RP1. */
+	(void)readl(bp->regs + MACB_NCR);
 	spin_unlock(&bp->lock);
 
 	if (CIRC_SPACE(queue->tx_head, queue->tx_tail, bp->tx_ring_size) < 1)
